CSS Selectors: Choosing where to apply CSS

- ONE THING TO REMEMEBER: NO TAGS IN THE CSS FILE!!!

- ELEMENT SELECTOR
Choose the element Selector where you'd like your css rule to apply to. Applies to ALL ELEMENTS that 
have that particular tag
i.e.

index.html
<h2>Red</h2>
<h2>Green</h2>
<h2>Blue</h2>

styles.css
h2
{
    colour: red;
}
In this case, we're using an element selector (the name of the tag, in this case 'h2') and after the 
curly braces, we can define whatever css rules that we want (in this case, text colour = red). 'Red', 
'Green' and 'Blue' ALL turn red because they all have the 'h2' element selector.

- CLASS SELECTOR
Requires a special symbol (dot) then with no spaces, write the name of the class
i.e.
.red-heading{
    color: red
}

A class is something we can add as an attribute to any html element.
i.e.

index.html
<h2 class="red-text">Red</h2>
<h2>Green</h2>
<h2>Blue</h2>

styles.css
.red-text{
    color: red;
}
Like saying let's group these particular elements into a class. Used for grouping elements in your html 
file to apply the same css rule to all of them.

You can tag different elements using the same class so that css style can apply to different tags. 
Doesn't matter if it's h2, p, a, etc; if they have that class, the rule will apply to it. 

- ID SELECTOR
Special symbol (hashtag). 
i.e.
#main {
    .color: red
}

Selects a particular id element and applies a certain rule.

i.e.
index.html
<h2 id="main">Red</h2>
<h2>Green</h2>
<h2>Blue</h2>

styles.css
#main {
    color:red;
}

ID vs. CLASS SELECTOR:
Class Selector - can be applied to MANY elements
Id Selector - should only be applied to ONE element in a single html file

- ATTRIBUTE SELECTOR
e.g. <h1 id=, class=, href=, src=, draggable=, alt=, etc>

html element[attribute]{
    css_property: value
    }
e.g.
p[draggable]{ 
    color:red
}
This particular case selects all p elements with the attribute 'draggable' and applies the css style to 
them
i.e.
index.html
<p draggable="true">Drag Me</p>
<p>Don't drag me</p>
<p>Don't drag me</p>

styles.css
p[draggable]{
    color:red;
}

Result: Drag Me is in red, both Don't drag me's in default colour

TAKING IT 1 STEP FURTHER...
index.html
<p draggable="true">Drag Me</p>
<p draggable="false">Don't drag me</p>
<p draggable="false">Don't drag me</p>

styles.css
p[draggable="false"]{
    color: red;
}

Result: Both Don't drag me is in red, Drag me in default colour

- UNIVERSAL SELECTOR
Select all
e.g.
* {
    color:red
}

i.e.
index.html
<h1 class="title">Hello</h1>
<h2 id="heading">World</h2>
<p draggable="true">
    This is a website
</p>

styles.css
* {
    color: red;
}

Result: Everything is in red